# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: styled-components
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:styled-components/cascading-style-sheets] CSS is designed to enable the separation of content and presentation, including layout, colors, and fonts.
[src:styled-components/cascading-style-sheets] Separation of formatting and content also makes it feasible to present the same markup page in different styles for different rendering methods, such as on-screen, in print, by voice (via speech-based browser or screen reader), and on Braille-based tactile devices.
[src:styled-components/cascading-style-sheets] CSS also has rules for alternative formatting if the content is accessed on a mobile device.
[src:styled-components/cascading-style-sheets] The name *cascading* comes from the specified priority scheme to determine which declaration applies if more than one declaration of a property match a particular element.
[src:styled-components/cascading-style-sheets] This cascading priority scheme is predictable.
[src:styled-components/cascading-style-sheets] The CSS specifications are maintained by the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C).
[src:styled-components/cascading-style-sheets] Internet media type (MIME type) `text/css` is registered for use with CSS by RFC 2318 (March 1998).
[src:styled-components/cascading-style-sheets] The W3C operates a free CSS validation service for CSS documents.
[src:styled-components/cascading-style-sheets] In addition to HTML, other markup languages support the use of CSS including XHTML, plain XML, SVG, and XUL.
[src:styled-components/cascading-style-sheets] CSS is also used in the GTK widget toolkit.
[src:styled-components/cascading-style-sheets] CSS has a simple syntax and uses a number of English keywords to specify the names of various style properties.
[src:styled-components/cascading-style-sheets] A style sheet consists of a list of *rules*.
[src:styled-components/cascading-style-sheets] Each rule or rule-set consists of one or more *selectors*, and a *declaration block*.
[src:styled-components/cascading-style-sheets] In CSS, *selectors* declare which part of the markup a style applies to by matching tags and attributes in the markup itself.
[src:styled-components/cascading-style-sheets] Classes and IDs are case-sensitive, start with letters, and can include alphanumeric characters, hyphens, and underscores.
[src:styled-components/cascading-style-sheets] A class may apply to any number of instances of any element.
[src:styled-components/cascading-style-sheets] An ID may only be applied to a single element.
[src:styled-components/cascading-style-sheets] One example of a widely used pseudo-class is `:hover`, which identifies content only when the user "points to" the visible element, usually by holding the mouse cursor over it.
[src:styled-components/cascading-style-sheets] It is appended to a selector as in `a:hover` or `#elementid:hover`.
[src:styled-components/cascading-style-sheets] A pseudo-class classifies document elements, such as `:link` or `:visited`, whereas a *pseudo-element* makes a selection that may consist of partial elements, such as `::first-line` or `::first-letter`.
[src:styled-components/cascading-style-sheets] Note the distinction between the double-colon notation used for pseudo-elements and the single-colon notation used for pseudo-classes.
[src:styled-components/cascading-style-sheets] Multiple simple selectors may be joined using combinators to specify elements by location, element type, id, class, or any combination thereof.
[src:styled-components/cascading-style-sheets] The order of the selectors is important.
[src:styled-components/cascading-style-sheets] For example, `div .myClass {color: red;}` applies to all elements of class myClass that are inside div elements, whereas `.myClass div {color: red;}` applies to all div elements that are inside elements of class myClass.
[src:styled-components/cascading-style-sheets] This is not to be confused with concatenated identifiers such as `div.myClass {color: red;}` which applies to div elements of class myClass.
[src:styled-components/cascading-style-sheets] The following table provides a summary of selector syntax indicating usage and the version of CSS that introduced it.
[src:styled-components/cascading-style-sheets] A declaration block consists of a pair of braces (`{}`) enclosing a semicolon-separated list of *declarations*.
[src:styled-components/cascading-style-sheets] Each declaration itself consists of a *property*, a colon (`:`), and a *value*.
[src:styled-components/cascading-style-sheets] Optional white-space may be around the declaration block, declarations, colons, and semi-colons for readability.
[src:styled-components/cascading-style-sheets] Properties are specified in the CSS standard.
[src:styled-components/cascading-style-sheets] Each property has a set of possible values.
[src:styled-components/cascading-style-sheets] Some properties can affect any type of element, and others apply only to particular groups of elements.
[src:styled-components/cascading-style-sheets] Values may be keywords, such as "center" or "inherit", or numerical values, such as `200px` (200 pixels), `50vw` (50 percent of the viewport width) or 80% (80 percent of the parent element's width).
[src:styled-components/cascading-style-sheets] Color values can be specified with keywords (e.g.
[src:styled-components/cascading-style-sheets] `rgb(255, 0, 0)`), RGBA values that specify both color and alpha transparency (e.g.
[src:styled-components/cascading-style-sheets] Non-zero numeric values representing linear measures must include a length unit, which is either an alphabetic code or abbreviation, as in `200px` or `50vw`; or a percentage sign, as in `80%`.
[src:styled-components/cascading-style-sheets] These eight units were a feature of CSS 1 and retained in all subsequent revisions.
[src:styled-components/cascading-style-sheets] The proposed CSS Values and Units Module Level 3 will, if adopted as a W3C Recommendation, provide seven further length units: `ch`; `Q`; `rem`; `vh`; `vmax`; `vmin`; and `vw`.
[src:styled-components/cascading-style-sheets] Before CSS, nearly all presentational attributes of HTML documents were contained within the HTML markup.
[src:styled-components/cascading-style-sheets] That is, all font colors, background styles, element alignments, borders, and sizes had to be explicitly described (often repeatedly) within the HTML.
[src:styled-components/cascading-style-sheets] CSS lets authors move much of that information to another file, the style sheet, resulting in considerably simpler HTML.
[src:styled-components/cascading-style-sheets] And additionally, as more and more devices are able to access responsive web pages, different screen sizes and layouts begin to appear.
[src:styled-components/cascading-style-sheets] Customizing a website for each device size is costly and increasingly difficult.
[src:styled-components/cascading-style-sheets] The modular nature of CSS means that styles can be reused in different parts of a site or even across sites, promoting consistency and efficiency.
[src:styled-components/cascading-style-sheets] For example, headings (`h1` elements), sub-headings (`h2`), sub-sub-headings (`h3`), etc., are defined structurally using HTML.
[src:styled-components/cascading-style-sheets] In print and on the screen, choice of font, size, color and emphasis for these elements is *presentational*.
[src:styled-components/cascading-style-sheets] Before CSS, document authors who wanted to assign such typographic characteristics to, say, all `h2` headings had to repeat HTML presentational markup for each occurrence of that heading type.
[src:styled-components/cascading-style-sheets] This made documents more complex, larger, and more error-prone and difficult to maintain.
[src:styled-components/cascading-style-sheets] CSS allows the separation of presentation from structure.
[src:styled-components/cascading-style-sheets] CSS can define color, font, text alignment, size, borders, spacing, layout and many other typographic characteristics, and can do so independently for on-screen and printed views.
[src:styled-components/cascading-style-sheets] CSS also defines non-visual styles, such as reading speed and emphasis for aural text readers.
[src:styled-components/cascading-style-sheets] The W3C has now deprecated the use of all presentational HTML markup.
[src:styled-components/cascading-style-sheets] The advantages of this may not be immediately clear but the power of CSS becomes more apparent when the style properties are placed in an internal style element or, even better, an external CSS file.
[src:styled-components/cascading-style-sheets] All `h1` elements in the document will then automatically become red without requiring any explicit code.
[src:styled-components/cascading-style-sheets] rather than by laboriously going through the document and changing the color for each individual `h1` element.
[src:styled-components/cascading-style-sheets] This further decouples the styling from the HTML document and makes it possible to restyle multiple documents by simply editing a shared external CSS file.
[src:styled-components/css-css-scoping] The **CSS scoping** module defines the CSS scoping and encapsulation mechanisms, focusing on the Shadow DOM scoping mechanism.
[src:styled-components/css-css-scoping] CSS styles are either global in scope or scoped to a shadow tree.
[src:styled-components/css-css-scoping] Globally scoped styles apply to all the elements in the node tree that match the selector, including custom elements in that tree, but not to the shadow trees composing each custom element.
[src:styled-components/css-css-scoping] Selectors and their associated style definitions don't bleed between scopes.
[src:styled-components/css-css-scoping] Within the CSS of a shadow tree, selectors don't select elements outside the tree, either in the global scope or in other shadow trees.
[src:styled-components/css-css-scoping] Each custom element has its own shadow tree, which contains all the components that make up the custom element (but not the custom element, or "host", itself).
[src:styled-components/css-css-scoping] Sometimes it's useful to be able to style a host from inside the shadow tree context.
[src:styled-components/css-css-scoping] An introduction to the different technologies used to create reusable web components — custom elements whose functionality is encapsulated away from the rest of your code.
[src:styled-components/css-css-scoping] Shadow DOM fundamentals, including attaching a shadow DOM to an element, adding to the shadow DOM tree, and styling.
[src:styled-components/css-css-scoping] Defining reusable HTML structure using `<template>` and `<slot>` elements, and using that structure inside web components.
[src:styled-components/css-css-scoping] Introduction to the Custom Elements API, the JavaScript API used to create custom elements that encapsulate functionality.
[src:styled-components/css-in-js] These libraries allow the creation of styled components using tagged template literals.
[src:styled-components/css-in-js] Some outcomes that may be achieved through CSS-in-JS can not be obtained using traditional CSS techniques.
[src:styled-components/css-in-js] It is possible to make the styles dynamic in line with just a few conditional statements.
[src:styled-components/css-in-js] Programmers may also write more modular code, with CSS being encapsulated in the same block as the programmer's JavaScript, scoping it to that module only.
[src:styled-components/css-in-js] CSS-in-JS is used by Reddit, Patreon, Target, Atlassian, Vogue, GitHub and Coinbase.
[src:styled-components/css-reference] Use this **CSS reference** to browse an alphabetical index of all of the standard CSS properties, pseudo-classes, pseudo-elements, data types, functional notations and at-rules.
[src:styled-components/css-reference] You can also browse key CSS concepts and a list of selectors organized by type.
[src:styled-components/css-reference] Also included is a brief DOM-CSS / CSSOM reference.
[src:styled-components/css-reference] See the index of *selectors*, *pseudo-classes*, and *pseudo-elements* below.
[src:styled-components/css-reference] The syntax for each specified *value* depends on the data type defined for each specified *property*.
[src:styled-components/css-reference] For a beginner-level introduction to the syntax of selectors, see our guide on CSS Selectors.
[src:styled-components/css-reference] Be aware that any syntax error in a rule definition invalidates the entire rule.
[src:styled-components/css-reference] Invalid rules are ignored by the browser.
[src:styled-components/css-reference] Note that CSS rule definitions are entirely (Unicode) text-based, whereas DOM-CSS / CSSOM (the rule management system) is object-based.
[src:styled-components/css-reference] As the structure of at-rules varies widely, please see At-rule to find the syntax of the specific one you want.
[src:styled-components/css-reference] The following are the various selectors, which allow styles to be conditional based on various features of elements within the DOM.
[src:styled-components/css-reference] Specifies that both `A` and `B` elements are selected.
[src:styled-components/css-reference] This is a grouping method to select several matching elements.
[src:styled-components/css-reference] Combinators are selectors that establish a relationship between two or more simple selectors, such as "`A` is a child of `B`" or "`A` is adjacent to `B`", creating a complex selector.
[src:styled-components/css-reference] Specifies that the elements selected by both `A` and `B` have the same parent and that the element selected by `B` immediately follows the element selected by `A` horizontally.
[src:styled-components/css-reference] Specifies that the elements selected by both `A` and `B` share the same parent and that the element selected by `A` comes before—but not necessarily immediately before—the element selected by `B`.
[src:styled-components/css-reference] Specifies that the element selected by `B` is the direct child of the element selected by `A`.
[src:styled-components/css-reference] Specifies that the element selected by `B` is a descendant of the element selected by `A`, but is not necessarily a direct child.
[src:styled-components/css-reference] Specifies that the element selected by `B` is located within the table column specified by `A`.
[src:styled-components/css-reference] Elements which span multiple columns are considered to be a member of all of those columns.
[src:styled-components/css-reference] Specifies a special state of the selected element(s).
[src:styled-components/css-reference] Represents entities that are not included in HTML.
[src:styled-components/css-reference] See also selectors in the Selectors specification and the pseudo-element specification.
[src:styled-components/cssstylesheet] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:styled-components/cssstylesheet] It’s been available across browsers since July 2015.
[src:styled-components/cssstylesheet] The **`CSSStyleSheet`** interface represents a single CSS stylesheet, and lets you inspect and modify the list of rules contained in the stylesheet.
[src:styled-components/cssstylesheet] It inherits properties and methods from its parent, `StyleSheet`.
[src:styled-components/cssstylesheet] A stylesheet consists of a collection of `CSSRule` objects representing each of the rules in the stylesheet.
[src:styled-components/cssstylesheet] The rules are contained in a `CSSRuleList`, which can be obtained from the stylesheet's `cssRules` property.
[src:styled-components/cssstylesheet] Another rule might be an *at-rule* such as `@import` or `@media`, and so forth.
[src:styled-components/cssstylesheet] See the Obtaining a StyleSheet section for the various ways a `CSSStyleSheet` object can be obtained.
[src:styled-components/cssstylesheet] A `CSSStyleSheet` object can also be directly constructed.
[src:styled-components/cssstylesheet] The constructor, and the `CSSStyleSheet.replace()`, and `CSSStyleSheet.replaceSync()` methods are newer additions to the specification, enabling *Constructable Stylesheets*.
[src:styled-components/cssstylesheet] To apply a `CSSStyleSheet` to a document or shadow root, assign it to the `Document.adoptedStyleSheets` or `ShadowRoot.adoptedStyleSheets` property, respectively.
[src:styled-components/cssstylesheet] Returns a live `CSSRuleList` which maintains an up-to-date list of the `CSSRule` objects that comprise the stylesheet.
[src:styled-components/cssstylesheet] If this stylesheet is imported into the document using an `@import` rule, the `ownerRule` property returns the corresponding `CSSImportRule`; otherwise, this property's value is `null`.
[src:styled-components/cssstylesheet] Deletes the rule at the specified index into the stylesheet's rule list.
[src:styled-components/cssstylesheet] Inserts a new rule at the specified position in the stylesheet, given the textual representation of the rule.
[src:styled-components/cssstylesheet] Asynchronously replaces the content of the stylesheet and returns a `Promise` that resolves with the updated `CSSStyleSheet`.
[src:styled-components/cssstylesheet] Synchronously replaces the content of the stylesheet.
[src:styled-components/cssstylesheet] The `rules` property is functionally identical to the standard `cssRules` property; it returns a live `CSSRuleList` which maintains an up-to-date list of all of the rules in the style sheet.
[src:styled-components/cssstylesheet] Adds a new rule to the stylesheet given the selector to which the style applies and the style block to apply to the matching elements.
[src:styled-components/cssstylesheet] This differs from `insertRule()`, which takes the textual representation of the entire rule as a single string.
[src:styled-components/cssstylesheet] Functionally identical to `deleteRule()`; removes the rule at the specified index from the stylesheet's rule list.
[src:styled-components/cssstylesheet] A stylesheet is associated with at most one `Document`, which it applies to (unless disabled).
[src:styled-components/cssstylesheet] A list of `CSSStyleSheet` objects for a given document can be obtained using the `Document.styleSheets` property.
[src:styled-components/cssstylesheet] A specific style sheet can also be accessed from its *owner* object (`Node` or `CSSImportRule`), if any.
[src:styled-components/cssstylesheet] A `CSSStyleSheet` object is created and inserted into the document's `Document.styleSheets` list automatically by the browser, when a stylesheet is loaded for a document.
[src:styled-components/global-objects-proxy] It’s been available across browsers since September 2016.
[src:styled-components/global-objects-proxy] The **`Proxy`** object enables you to create a proxy for another object, which can intercept and redefine fundamental operations for that object.
[src:styled-components/global-objects-proxy] The `Proxy` object allows you to create an object that can be used in place of the original object, but which may redefine fundamental `Object` operations like getting, setting, and defining properties.
[src:styled-components/global-objects-proxy] Proxy objects are commonly used to log property accesses, validate, format, or sanitize inputs, and so on.
[src:styled-components/global-objects-proxy] For example, this code creates a proxy for the `target` object.
[src:styled-components/global-objects-proxy] Here we've provided an implementation of the `get()` handler, which intercepts attempts to access properties in the target.
[src:styled-components/global-objects-proxy] Handler functions are sometimes called *traps*, presumably because they trap calls to the target object.
[src:styled-components/global-objects-proxy] Proxies are often used with the `Reflect` object, which provides some methods with the same names as the `Proxy` traps.
[src:styled-components/global-objects-proxy] The `Reflect` methods provide the reflective semantics for invoking the corresponding object internal methods.
[src:styled-components/global-objects-proxy] The `Reflect` method still interacts with the object through object internal methods — it doesn't "de-proxify" the proxy if it's invoked on a proxy.
[src:styled-components/global-objects-proxy] If you use `Reflect` methods within a proxy trap, and the `Reflect` method call gets intercepted by the trap again, there may be infinite recursion.
[src:styled-components/global-objects-proxy] The following terms are used when talking about the functionality of proxies.
[src:styled-components/global-objects-proxy] The object passed as the second argument to the `Proxy` constructor.
[src:styled-components/global-objects-proxy] It contains the traps which define the behavior of the proxy.
[src:styled-components/global-objects-proxy] The function that defines the behavior for the corresponding object internal method.
[src:styled-components/global-objects-proxy] It is often used as storage backend for the proxy.
[src:styled-components/global-objects-proxy] Invariants (semantics that remain unchanged) regarding object non-extensibility or non-configurable properties are verified against the target.
[src:styled-components/global-objects-proxy] Semantics that remain unchanged when implementing custom operations.
[src:styled-components/global-objects-proxy] If your trap implementation violates the invariants of a handler, a `TypeError` will be thrown.
[src:styled-components/global-objects-proxy] However, the language doesn't provide any machinery to *directly* manipulate data stored in the object — rather, the object defines some internal methods specifying how it can be interacted with.
[src:styled-components/global-objects-proxy] There isn't anything special about this process in the language — it's just because ordinary objects, by default, have a `[[Get]]` internal method that is defined with this behavior.
[src:styled-components/global-objects-proxy] The `obj.x` property access syntax simply invokes the `[[Get]]` method on the object, and the object uses its own internal method implementation to determine what to return.
[src:styled-components/global-objects-proxy] As another example, arrays differ from normal objects, because they have a magic `length` property that, when modified, automatically allocates empty slots or removes elements from the array.
[src:styled-components/global-objects-proxy] Similarly, adding array elements automatically changes the `length` property.
[src:styled-components/global-objects-proxy] This is because arrays have a `[[DefineOwnProperty]]` internal method that knows to update `length` when an integer index is written to, or update the array contents when `length` is written to.
[src:styled-components/global-objects-proxy] Such objects whose internal methods have different implementations from ordinary objects are called *exotic objects*.
[src:styled-components/global-objects-proxy] `Proxy` enable developers to define their own exotic objects with full capacity.
[src:styled-components/global-objects-proxy] It's important to realize that all interactions with an object eventually boils down to the invocation of one of these internal methods, and that they are all customizable through proxies.
[src:styled-components/global-objects-proxy] This means almost no behavior (except certain critical invariants) is guaranteed in the language — everything is defined by the object itself.
[src:styled-components/global-objects-proxy] When you run `delete obj.x`, there's no guarantee that `"x" in obj` returns `false` afterwards — it depends on the object's implementations of `[[Delete]]` and `[[HasProperty]]`.
[src:styled-components/global-objects-proxy] A `delete obj.x` may log things to the console, modify some global state, or even define a new property instead of deleting the existing one, although these semantics should be avoided in your own code.
[src:styled-components/global-objects-proxy] All internal methods are called by the language itself, and are not directly accessible in JavaScript code.
[src:styled-components/global-objects-proxy] The `Reflect` namespace offers methods that do little more than call the internal methods, besides some input normalization/validation.
[src:styled-components/global-objects-proxy] In each trap's page, we list several typical situations when the trap is invoked, but these internal methods are called in *a lot* of places.
[src:styled-components/global-objects-proxy] For example, array methods read and write to array through these internal methods, so methods like `push()` would also invoke `get()` and `set()` traps.
[src:styled-components/global-objects-proxy] Most of the internal methods are straightforward in what they do.
[src:styled-components/global-objects-proxy] The only two that may be confusable are `[[Set]]` and `[[DefineOwnProperty]]`.
[src:styled-components/global-objects-proxy] For normal objects, the former invokes setters; the latter doesn't.
[src:styled-components/global-objects-proxy] For example, class fields use the `[[DefineOwnProperty]]` semantic, which is why setters defined in the superclass are not invoked when a field is declared on the derived class.
[src:styled-components/global-objects-proxy] In this example, the number `37` gets returned as the default value when the property name is not in the object.
[src:styled-components/global-objects-proxy] In this example, we are using a native JavaScript object to which our proxy will forward all operations that are applied to it.
[src:styled-components/global-objects-proxy] Note that while this "no-op" works for plain JavaScript objects, it does not work for native objects, such as DOM elements, `Map` objects, or anything that has internal slots.
[src:styled-components/global-objects-proxy] See no private field forwarding for more information.
[src:styled-components/global-objects-proxy] A proxy is still another object with a different identity — it's a *proxy* that operates between the wrapped object and the outside.
[src:styled-components/global-objects-proxy] As such, the proxy does not have direct access to the original object's private elements.
[src:styled-components/global-objects-proxy] This is because when the proxy's `get` trap is invoked, the `this` value is the `proxy` instead of the original `secret`, so `#secret` is not accessible.
[src:styled-components/global-objects-proxy] Some native JavaScript objects have properties called *internal slots*, which are not accessible from JavaScript code.
[src:styled-components/global-objects-proxy] For example, `Map` objects have an internal slot called `[[MapData]]`, which stores the key-value pairs of the map.
[src:styled-components/global-objects-proxy] You have to use the "`this`-recovering" proxy illustrated above to work around this.
[src:styled-components/global-objects-proxy] With a `Proxy`, you can easily validate the passed value for an object.
[src:styled-components/global-objects-proxy] In this example we use `Proxy` to toggle an attribute of two different elements: so when we set the attribute on one element, the attribute is unset on the other one.
[src:styled-components/global-objects-proxy] We create a `view` object which is a proxy for an object with a `selected` property.
[src:styled-components/global-objects-proxy] The proxy handler defines the `set()` handler.
[src:styled-components/global-objects-proxy] When we assign an HTML element to `view.selected`, the element's `'aria-selected'` attribute is set to `true`.
[src:styled-components/global-objects-proxy] If we then assign a different element to `view.selected`, this element's `'aria-selected'` attribute is set to `true` and the previous element's `'aria-selected'` attribute is automatically set to `false`.
[src:styled-components/global-objects-proxy] The `products` proxy object evaluates the passed value and converts it to an array if needed.
[src:styled-components/global-objects-proxy] The object also supports an extra property called `latestBrowser` both as a getter and a setter.
